#Text=By Joseph Conrad
#Text=Kennedy is a country doctor , and lives in Colebrook , on the shores of Eastbay .
#Text=The high ground rising abruptly behind the red roofs of the little town crowds the quaint High Street against the wall which defends it from the sea .

#Text=Beyond the sea-wall there curves for miles in a vast and regular sweep the barren beach of shingle , with the village of Brenzett standing out darkly across the water , a spire in a clump of trees ; and still further out the perpendicular column of a lighthouse , looking in the distance no bigger than a lead pencil , marks the vanishing-point of the land .

#Text=The country at the back of Brenzett is low and flat , but the bay is fairly well sheltered from the seas , and occasionally a big ship , windbound or through stress of weather , makes use of the anchoring ground a mile and a half due north from you as you stand at the back door of the “ Ship Inn ” in Brenzett .

#Text=A dilapidated windmill near by lifting its shattered arms from a mound no loftier than a rubbish heap , and a Martello tower squatting at the water ’s edge half a mile to the south of the Coastguard cottages , are familiar to the skippers of small craft .

#Text=These are the official seamarks for the patch of trustworthy bottom represented on the Admiralty charts by an irregular oval of dots enclosing several figures six , with a tiny anchor engraved among them , and the legend “ mud and shells ” over all .
#Text=The brow of the upland overtops the square tower of the Colebrook Church .
#Text=The slope is green and looped by a white road .
#Text=Ascending along this road , you open a valley broad and shallow , a wide green trough of pastures and hedges merging inland into a vista of purple tints and flowing lines closing the view .
#Text=In this valley down to Brenzett and Colebrook and up to Darnford , the market town fourteen miles away , lies the practice of my friend Kennedy .
#Text=He had begun life as surgeon in the Navy , and afterwards had been the companion of a famous traveller , in the days when there were continents with unexplored interiors .
#Text=His papers on the fauna and flora made him known to scientific societies .
#Text=And now he had come to a country practice -- from choice .
#Text=The penetrating power of his mind , acting like a corrosive fluid , had destroyed his ambition , I fancy .
#Text=His intelligence is of a scientific order , of an investigating habit , and of that unappeasable curiosity which believes that there is a particle of a general truth in every mystery .
#Text=A good many years ago now , on my return from abroad , he invited me to stay with him .
#Text=I came readily enough , and as he could not neglect his patients to keep me company , he took me on his rounds -- thirty miles or so of an afternoon , sometimes .
#Text=I waited for him on the roads ; the horse reached after the leafy twigs , and , sitting in the dogcart , I could hear Kennedy ’s laugh through the half-open door left open of some cottage .
#Text=He had a big , hearty laugh that would have fitted a man twice his size , a brisk manner , a bronzed face , and a pair of grey , profoundly attentive eyes .
#Text=He had the talent of making people talk to him freely , and an inexhaustible patience in listening to their tales .

#Text=One day , as we trotted out of a large village into a shady bit of road , I saw on our left hand a low , black cottage , with diamond panes in the windows , a creeper on the end wall , a roof of shingle , and some roses climbing on the rickety trellis-work of the tiny porch .
#Text=Kennedy pulled up to a walk .
#Text=A woman , in full sunlight , was throwing a dripping blanket over a line stretched between two old apple-trees .

#Text=And as the bobtailed , long-necked chestnut , trying to get his head , jerked the left hand , covered by a thick dog-skin glove , the doctor raised his voice over the hedge : “ How ’s your child , Amy ? ”

#Text=I had the time to see her dull face , red , not with a mantling blush , but as if her flat cheeks had been vigorously slapped , and to take in the squat figure , the scanty , dusty brown hair drawn into a tight knot at the back of the head .
#Text=She looked quite young .
#Text=With a distinct catch in her breath , her voice sounded low and timid .
#Text=“ He ’s well , thank you . ”
#Text=We trotted again .
#Text=“ A young patient of yours , ” I said ; and the doctor , flicking the chestnut absently , muttered , “ Her husband used to be . ”
#Text=“ She seems a dull creature , ” I remarked listlessly .
#Text=“ Precisely , ” said Kennedy .
#Text=“ She is very passive .

#Text=It ’s enough to look at the red hands hanging at the end of those short arms , at those slow , prominent brown eyes , to know the inertness of her mind -- an inertness that one would think made it everlastingly safe from all the surprises of imagination .
#Text=And yet which of us is safe ?
#Text=At any rate , such as you see her , she had enough imagination to fall in love .

#Text=She ’s the daughter of one Isaac Foster , who from a small farmer has sunk into a shepherd ; the beginning of his misfortunes dating from his runaway marriage with the cook of his widowed father -- a well-to-do , apoplectic grazier , who passionately struck his name off his will , and had been heard to utter threats against his life .
#Text=But this old affair , scandalous enough to serve as a motive for a Greek tragedy , arose from the similarity of their characters .

#Text=There are other tragedies , less scandalous and of a subtler poignancy , arising from irreconcilable differences and from that fear of the Incomprehensible that hangs over all our heads -- over all our heads ... . ”
